segments.text: Not every World War II veteran served overseas as they had jobs or were being trained for essential jobs stateside.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Such was the case for Dr. Gordon Pratt, who joined the Navy in 1943 and was put in the B-12 program.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: It was a college training program that sent future commissioned officers to colleges and universities to complete their training and to help the war effort as a result of their education.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Between 1943 and 1946, more than 125,000 men were enrolled in V-12.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: They included such servicemen as football coach George Allen, Senator Howard Baker, Senator Robert F. Kennedy, Johnny Carson, and Jack Lemmon, and a dental student named Gordon Pratt from Dallas.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: After the war, he served as the dentist for nearly two years aboard the USS President Adams, a World War II transport ship, and then later at the Corpus Christi Naval Air Station.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Dr. Pratt practiced for 40 years as a dentist in Bryan until he retired in 1997.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: One of his five children, Gordon Pratt Jr., has been a dentist here for nearly 25 years.
